# Configuration

DataGenerator takes two inputs: a catalog workbook and a run configuration. The catalog is
the menu you choose from. The run configuration is the order you place.

## The catalog workbook

The workbook `data-generator.xlsx` holds the reference data, read-only. The reader uses these
sheets:

| Sheet | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| `Industry` | Industry verticals. Column A is the name, column B the description. |
| `SourceType` | Source-system types. Columns: code, type, description. |
| `Storage` | Target storage names. |
| `Attributes` | Entity and attribute definitions (CDM and D365). The reader builds the entity catalog from this sheet. |

The `Attributes` sheet drives the entity catalog. Each row carries the schema area, entity
name, attribute name, CDM data type, and the attribute purpose. The reader groups rows by
entity and resolves every entity's attribute list in one streaming pass.

> **Note**: The reader streams the large `Attributes` sheet row by row, so a workbook with more
> than one hundred thousand attribute rows loads without holding the whole sheet in memory.

## The run configuration

The run configuration is a JSON document with three parts: the run header, the entity profiles,
and the targets. See [Run configuration](../guides/run-configuration.md) for the full reference,
and [samples/run-config.sample.json](../../samples/run-config.sample.json) for a complete example.

The run header names one industry and one source type by their workbook values. The loader
validates them against the catalog, so a typo fails at load rather than mid-run.

## Environment variables

| Variable | Used by | Purpose |
|----------|---------|---------|
| `APPLICATIONINSIGHTS_CONNECTION_STRING` | All hosts | Routes logs to Application Insights. |
| `DATAGEN_WORKBOOK` | Functions host | Path to the catalog workbook. |
| `DATAGEN_CONFIG` | Functions host | Path to the run configuration. |
| `DATAGEN_OFFLINE` | Functions host | Set to `true` to skip Foundry and use placeholder values. |

